</author>
<date year="2025" month="September"/>
<abstract>
<t>RepSec defines an interoperable signaling layer for exchanging signed reputation and revocation assertions alongside data. This -01 updates field names, clarifies security considerations, and aligns references for xml2rfc v3.</t>
</abstract>
</front>
<middle>
<section anchor="intro" numbered="true">
<name>Introduction</name>
<t>RepSec provides portable assertions of provenance, reputation, and revocation to complement existing transports and application protocols.</t>
</section>
<section anchor="terminology" numbered="true">
<name>Terminology</name>
<t>
The key words
<bcp14>MUST</bcp14>
,
<bcp14>MUST NOT</bcp14>
,
<bcp14>REQUIRED</bcp14>
,
<bcp14>SHALL</bcp14>
,
<bcp14>SHALL NOT</bcp14>
,
<bcp14>SHOULD</bcp14>
,
<bcp14>SHOULD NOT</bcp14>
,
<bcp14>RECOMMENDED</bcp14>
,
<bcp14>NOT RECOMMENDED</bcp14>
,
<bcp14>MAY</bcp14>
, and
<bcp14>OPTIONAL</bcp14>
are to be interpreted as described in
<xref target="RFC2119"/>
and
<xref target="RFC8174"/>
.
</t>
</section>
<section anchor="arch" numbered="true">
<name>Protocol Overview</name>
<t>RepSec defines three roles:</t>
<ul>
<li>
<t>
<em>Issuer</em>
: produces signed assertions.
</t>
</li>
<li>
<t>
<em>Presenter</em>
: attaches assertions to exchanges.
</t>
</li>
<li>
<t>
<em>Verifier</em>
: validates and enforces policy.
</t>
</li>
</ul>
<t>Encodings: JSON/CBOR. Signatures: JOSE/COSE. Transport bindings: HTTPS and message queues.</t>
</section>
<section anchor="security" numbered="true">
<name>Security Considerations</name>
<t>
Implementations
<bcp14>MUST</bcp14>
validate signatures, freshness, and consult revocation lists. TLS 1.3
<xref target="RFC8446"/>
is RECOMMENDED.
</t>
</section>
<section anchor="iana" numbered="true">
<name>IANA Considerations</name>
<t>This document has no IANA actions.</t>
</section>
